Content: Select TWO sentences from Passage 1 that show that Ellen is willing to consider another person's point of view.

A.Choice: “I saw that she still wore the same gloomy expression of countenance, which had been manifested in the morning; and I was disposed to remove from her mind the evil influence, by a plain common-sense conversation.” (paragraph 5)

B.Choice: “'I have frequently heard you say that you would not be confined to house-hold duties and that you disliked the millinery business altogether, because you could not have your evenings for leisure.'” (paragraph 6)

C.Choice: “'What difference does it make,' said I, 'whether you shall be awaked [sic] by a bell, or the noisy bustle of a farm-house?'” (paragraph 10)

D.Choice: “Ellen's hearty laugh interrupted my description — and presently we proceeded, very pleasantly, to compare a country life with a factory life in Lowell.” (paragraph 13)

Key.Rationale: This shows that Ellen is willing to listen to her friend's point of view and have a pleasant discussion about how they each see things.

E.Choice: “Her scowl of discontent had departed, and she was prepared to consider the subject candidly.” (paragraph 13)

Key.Rationale: This shows that Ellen is willing to think about the differences between factory life and farm life calmly and without anger.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
Which sentence states a theme of Passage 1?

A.Choice: Hard work pays off in the end.

B.Choice: Country life is better than city life.

C.Choice: Employers must treat workers with respect.

D.Choice: It is important ot consider both sides of an argument.

Key.Rationale: The narrator urges Ellen to look at all the benefits of their situation and not only dwell on the negative aspects.

Content: Fill in the bubbles before TWO sentences that support the answer in Part A.

:box:	 :MC-A: “And so, Ellen,” said I, “you think it unpleasant to rise so early in the morning, and be confined in the noisy mill so many hours in the day. :MC-B: And I think so, too. :MC-C: All this, and much more, is very annoying, no doubt. :MC-D: But we must not forget that there are advantages, as well as disadvantages, in this employment, as in every other. :MC-E: If we expect to find all sun-shine and flowers in any station in life, we shall most surely be disappointed. :MC-F: We are very busily engaged during the day; but then we have the evening to ourselves, with no one to dictate to or control us. :MC-G: I have frequently heard you say that you would not be confined to house-hold duties and that you disliked the millinery business altogether, because you could not have your evenings for leisure. :MC-H: You know that in Lowell we have schools, lectures, and meetings of every description, for moral and intellectual improvement.” (paragraph 6)

Key.Rationale: This sentence argues that all jobs have both positive and negative characteristics.
This sentence further develops the theme by suggesting that if we only expect ease, we are destined for disappointment.

Content: How do the repeated references to the ringing bell affect the dialogue between the narrator and Ellen throughout Passage 1?

A.Choice: They show what the narrator has done to improve her life.

B.Choice: They add to the tension of the choice Ellen is trying to make.

Key.Rationale: The bell is associated with noise and described as being noisy; this imagery causes tension for Ellen.

C.Choice: They provide a contrast for the work the women do in the mill.

D.Choice: They help readers understand why Ellen wants to stay in the city.

Content: What does the phrase “destitute of friends” suggest in paragraph 7?

A.Choice: that Ellen considers friends unimportant

B.Choice: that the women may lose their friendships

Key.Rationale: Ellen is suggesting that a loss of money will lead to a loss of friends. She is using the word “friends” ironically.

C.Choice: that the friendships the women make are strong

D.Choice: that Ellen is concerned about her friends' well-being

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
How is the narrator's point of view different from Ellen's?

A.Choice: The narrator thinks that the work the women do in the mill is easy.

B.Choice: The narrator recognizes the benefits of living and working in Lowell.

Key.Rationale: The narrator sees the positive outcomes of living and working in Lowell while Ellen expresses the hardships of living and working in Lowell.

C.Choice: The narrator enjoys the sounds of mechanical equipment heard in the city.

D.Choice: The narrator acknowledges that there is not enough time for leisure in Lowell.

Content: Select the sentence from Passage 1 that supports the answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “'And so, Ellen,' said I, 'you think it unpleasant to rise so early in the morning, and be confined in the noisy mill so many hours in the day.'” (paragraph 6)

B.Choice: “'But we must not forget that there are advantages, as well as disadvantages, in this employment, as in every other.'” (paragraph 6)

Key.Rationale: There are both advantages and disadvantages of living and working in Lowell. This quote presents both the narrator's and Ellen's attitude.

C.Choice: “'All that is very true,' replied Ellen, 'but if we were to attend every public institution, and every evening school which offers itself for our improvement, we might spend every farthing of our earnings, and even more.'” (paragraph 7)

D.Choice: “'But then,' said Ellen, 'country people have none of the clattering of machinery constantly dinning in their ears.'” (paragraph 11)

Content: Passage 1 and Passage 3 present the same story in different formats. Which element of the story is emphasized by listening to the audio clip in Passage 3?

A.Choice: Ellen's thoughts about living and working on a farm

B.Choice: the narrator's experiences working in the mill

C.Choice: Ellen's attitude toward living in the mill town

Key.Rationale: The tone that Ellen uses in the audio emphasizes her negative attitude toward working in the mill.

D.Choice: the narrator's ideas about life in the country

Content: Select TWO facts from Passage 2 that play a role in the story presented in Passage 1.

A.Choice: The boardinghouses were usually run by a female keeper.

B.Choice: Women working in Lowell mills mostly came from farms and small towns.

Key.Rationale: The women came to Lowell to find opportunities that they could not find in their small towns and farms.

C.Choice: Some women worked in small textile mills in the country before coming to the city.

D.Choice: Women who lived in Lowell boardinghouses often shared a bedroom with other women.

E.Choice: The cities provided mill workers with many social opportunities they did not have in small towns.

Key.Rationale: The women came to search for better opportunities in the cities like Lowell.

Content: Select TWO sentences from Passage 2 that support the inference that researchers are unsure of the effect that clicking moths have on bats.

A.Choice: “As a bat zips through the night sky, it sends out high-pitched squeaks, bouncing sound waves off of objects and unsuspecting prey.” (paragraph 5)

B.Choice: “While most insect victims would have trouble fighting back, many dive and loop to avoid enemies, and some have the added advantage of being poisonous.” (paragraph 5)

C.Choice: “Tiger moths have a special clicker called a tymbal built into their thorax.” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “Scientists have proposed a few reasons for the tymbal's success, ranging from its potential to startle a bat to its possible role as a 'jammer' that garbles the bats' hunting squeaks.” (paragraph 6)

Key.Rationale: This sentence shows that scientists have several possible theories in mind to explain the effect of the moths' clicking on bats, but they do not know for sure.

E.Choice: “The bat may recognize the clicks from the 11,000 tiger moth species, learning to avoid the critters after an initial bout of food poisoning.” (paragraph 7)

Key.Rationale: This sentence shows an additional theory about the effect of the moths' clicking on bats, which reinforces the inference that the scientists are not certain.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What are TWO central ideas of Passage 2?

A.Choice: Bats cannot see colors.

B.Choice: Bats use echolocation to hunt.

Key.Rationale: A key idea of the passage is how bats hunt using echolocation.

C.Choice: Many animals use echolocation.

D.Choice: Scientists study echolocation in moths.

E.Choice: One type of moth makes a clicking sound to avoid bats

Key.Rationale: A main idea of the passage is how moths avoid their predators by using a special sound.

Content: How does the author of Passage 2 develop the central ideas in Part A?

A.Choice: by discussing science experiments on bats

B.Choice: by explaining what people can learn from animals

C.Choice: by specifying the similarities between tiger moths and bats

D.Choice: by describing the relationship between bats and tiger moths

Key.Rationale: The passage develops the relationship of the bats and moths as one of predator and prey, showing that the moths can avoid being hunted by using a specific sound to disrupt the bats' use of echolocation.

Content: Read the following sentence from Passage 2.
:box:“Now, some researchers suspect one type of moth may have a way of effectively broadcasting its toxicity—the insect produces high-pitched sounds of its own.” (paragraph 5)
What is the effect of the word “toxicity” in this sentence?

A.Choice: It emphasizes the tiger moths' bright color.

B.Choice: It highlights the tiger moths' aggressiveness.

C.Choice: It shows the danger that tiger moths pose to bats.

Key.Rationale: The word “toxicity” shows that tiger moths are a danger for bats.

D.Choice: It shows how bats are affected by different noises.

Content: How does paragraph 1 of Passage 1 contribute to the development of the author's ideas?

A.Choice: By focusing on echolocation in bats, paragraph 1 explains how humans can benefit from studying echolocation.

B.Choice: By explaining specific uses for echolocation, paragraph 1 gives information about how bats developed the ability to echolocate.

C.Choice: By giving examples of objects that can be detected through echolocation, paragraph 1 explains how animals can avoid detection.

D.Choice: By giving a detailed description of how echolocation works, paragraph 1 helps the reader understand how other animals use echolocation.

Key.Rationale: The description of how echolocation works provides necessary context for readers to understand how other animals echolocate.

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
What is the purpose of Passage 2?

A.Choice: to discuss the various animals that use echolocation

B.Choice: to explain how a certain type of animal can counteract bat echolocation

Key.Rationale: Passage 2 focuses on how the tiger moth can counteract bat echolocation.

C.Choice: to explain that humans have developed military equipment by copying echolocation in bats

D.Choice: to give examples of the experiments that researchers have conducted to observe bat echolocation

Content: How does the author of Passage 2 develop the purpose?

A.Choice: by listing other ways that animals use echolocation

B.Choice: by explaining a theory for why tiger moths make certain sounds

Key.Rationale: Passage 1 explains the sounds made by animals trying to elude bats as confusing to the bats, but Passage 2 explains why it could be a way for tiger moths to communicate their toxicity.

C.Choice: by discussing several strategies used by tiger moths to avoid bats

D.Choice: by giving examples of specific bat behaviors related to echolocation

Content: This question has two parts. First, answer Part A. Then, answer Part B.
How does Passage 3 support the claim that the U.S. military would like to improve its sonar technology?

A.Choice: It illustrates how existing technology was developed through specific examples.

B.Choice: It gives statistical evidence that explains how technology has improved in the past.

C.Choice: It explains how bats echolocate and give examples of situations where echolocation might occur.

D.Choice: It describes how scientists train bats and observe specific behaviors to learn how echolocation works.

Key.Rationale: The passage highlights the research Jim Simmons is doing to gather data about how echolocation works.

Content: Select TWO sentences from Passage 3 that provide relevant support for the answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “'Bats make sounds, listen to echoes, and then see objects,' notes Simmons.” (paragraph 9)

B.Choice: “'We now know that bats have a method of doing synthetic aperture sonar while flying that not only determines the distance and direction of all the objects in a scene, but also reconstructs one specific object's shape.'” (paragraph 9)

Key.Rationale: This sentence discusses what scientists have learned from studying bats.

C.Choice: “In Simmons' experiments, the bats are trained to differentiate sounds with the time separation of those sounds shortened to test the bats' response.” (paragraph 10)

Key.Rationale: This sentence discusses the experiments scientists conduct to gather data about echolocation in bats.

D.Choice: “Today's electronic sonar processing can differentiate between echoes about 12 millionths of a second apart.” (paragraph 11)

E.Choice: “Bats have it down to 2 to 3 millionths of a second.” (paragraph 11)

Content: Fill in the bubbles to show how the authors of Passages 1 and 3 present information about sonar systems.

Key.Rationale: Both passages draw a comparison between echolocation and sonar technology.
Passage 3 presents sonar technology as a developing technology.
Passage 1 describes sonar technology as an already established method.

Content: Choose the correct word or phrase to replace the underlined part of the following sentence.
:box:Inspired by the creativity of those around her, t͟h͟e͟ ͟c͟i͟t͟y͟ ͟w͟a͟s͟ ͟h͟o͟m͟e͟ ͟t͟o͟ ͟m͟a͟n͟y͟ ͟a͟r͟t͟i͟s͟t͟i͟c͟ ͟b͟r͟e͟a͟k͟t͟h͟r͟o͟u͟g͟h͟s.

A.Choice: it was the environment Arias needed to succeed

B.Choice: a career in the arts came naturally

C.Choice: Arias flourished as an artist and a writer

Key.Rationale: The answer adds an appropriate subject given the introductory phrase.

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the correct words or phrases to replace the underlined parts of the following sentences.
:box:Arias decided she wanted to try writing her own translation and entered the c͟o͟m͟p͟e͟t͟i͟t͟i͟o͟n.

A.Choice: compitition

B.Choice: compatition

C.Choice: computition

D.Choice: correct as is

Key.Rationale: The word is spelled correctly, so no change is needed.

Content: :box:Arias had an a͟d͟v͟a͟n͟t͟a͟g͟e͟.͟ ͟S͟i͟n͟c͟e she was both a composer and a translator.

A.Choice: advantage because

Key.Rationale: The answer correctly combines the sentence with the fragment.

B.Choice: advantage however

C.Choice: advantage, but

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the correct word or phrase to replace the underlined part of the following sentence.
:box:Sitting at the piano, t͟h͟e͟ ͟s͟o͟n͟g͟ ͟s͟l͟o͟w͟l͟y͟ ͟c͟a͟m͟e͟ ͟t͟o͟g͟e͟t͟h͟e͟r.

A.Choice: music filled Arias' home

B.Choice: Arias worked on the translation

Key.Rationale: The answer adds an appropriate subject given the introductory phrase.

C.Choice: there was constant singing

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Which sentence uses correct grammar to replace the underlined part of the first paragraph?

A.Choice: Where natural resources brim, the Serengeti is a large region in Tanzania, a country in Africa.

B.Choice: The Serengeti is a large region in Tanzania, where natural resources brim, a country in Africa.

C.Choice: The Serengeti is a large region in Tanzania, a country, where natural resources brim, in Africa.

D.Choice: correct as is

Key.Rationale: This option places the clause correctly while avoiding a misplaced or dangling modifier.

Content: Choose the correct punctuation to replace the underlined part of the second paragraph.

A.Choice: massive, vibrant conservation area

Key.Rationale: This option correctly uses commas to separate the coordinate adjectives.

B.Choice: massive, vibrant, conservation area

C.Choice: massive, vibrant, conservation, area

D.Choice: correct as is

Content: Choose the correct spelling to replace the underlined part of the third paragraph.

A.Choice: esenntial

B.Choice: esentielle

C.Choice: essential

Key.Rationale: This is the correct spelling of the word.

D.Choice: correct as is
